{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600647/1930072601/0482.xml":{"full_text":"REAL ESTATE\nj j j\u25a0|\nHome-Owning and Building Section for Washington and Suburbs\nBUILDING-LOAN SESSIONS\nWILL SPUR HOME OWNING\n\u2022Officials From All Over U. S., Including Quinter,\nBauman and James of D. C, Will Meet\nTuesday in Grand Rapids.\nBUILDING and loan officials from all sections of the country,\nwho are custodians of approximately $8,000,000,000. used ex\nclusively for home financing, will meet in Grand Rapids, Mich.,\nTuesday in their thirty-eighth annual conventional to partici\n\u25a0pate in a program designed to encourage home ownership.\nWashington will be represented by William S. Quinter, secretary\nof the District Building and Loan League; Chapin Bauman, vice\npresident of the local league, and C. Clinton James, a member of\nthe board of directors of the United States Building and Loan League\nand a member of the Executive Committee of the local organization.\nMr. James will submit a report of the Legislative Committee of the\nnational body, of which he is chairman.\nBuilding and loan associations have attained a place of major\nImportance in the financing of homes. The combined total assets of\nsuch associations in all States of the country at the end of the past\nyear amounted to $8,695,154,000, an increase of more than $679,119,000\nover the previous year.\nWhile the recession in business\nactivities following the stock mar\nket slump last Fall had an ad\nverse effect on building and loan\nassociations, through withdrawal\nof deposits by members, reports\nindicate a steady recovery.\nProblems to Be Discussed.\nThe United States Building and\nLoan League, founded in 1893, will call\ntogether approximately 1.200 member\nassociations at the convention for a\ndiscussion of problems confronting\nthose engaged in home finance.\nSpeakers listed for the three-day\nSession will discuss real estate ap\npraisal, State supervision, the trend in\nreal estate values, the outlook for home\nownership, advanced accounting systems,\nthe merits of financial advertising, the\neducational courses provided through\nthe American Savings Building and\nLoan Institute, the importance of State\nlegislation, and the advantages of\nstronger organizations on the part of\nthose engaged in this business.\nGroup conferences and round-table\ndiscussions of attorneys participating\nIn building and loan work. State super\nvisors under whose direction building\nand loan organizations are operated,\nadvertising experts and other specialists,\nwill be held during the convention\nperiod.\nCarl H. Weber. Springfield, 111., presi\ndent of the National Association of\nBuilding and Loan Supervisors, will\npreside at the meetings of building and\nloan officials and State supervisors, and\nGeorge L. Bliss, New York City, presi\ndent of the American Savings Building\nand Loan Institute, will open the round\ntable discussions of this organization,\nwhich is the educational research part\nof the league.\nJames to Head Division Meeting.\nI. Friedlander. Houston, Tex., and\nWHfard K Denton, New York City,\ndirectors of the league, will preside at\nthe. advertising division meetings; C.\nClinton .James. Washington, director of\nthe league, will head the executive offi\ncers\u2019 division meeting: William A. Best,\nSecond vice president of the league,\nPittsburgh. Pa., will preside at the at\ntorneys\u2019 division meeting; Ward B.\nWhitlock, Springfield, 111., third vice\npresident of the league, will preside at\nthe league secretaries\u2019 division meet\ning, and Fred H. Jerome. Saginaw.\nMich., will preside at the meeting of\nthe accounting division. Lee C. Stidd,\nUnited States League director from\nPortland, Oreg., will preside at a meet\ning of the appraisal division.\nBraest A. Hale, president of the\nleague, will open the convention Tues\nday. after the meeting of the directors\nand the eExecutive Committee.\nThomas F. Holden, vice president of\nthe P. W. Dodge Corporation, New\nYork City, speaking on \u201cThe Real\nEstate and Business Outlook,\u201d will give\nthe building and loan men a picture of\nWhat to expect during the next year.\nAlong the same subject lines is the\naddress of James S. Natthews of the\nBabson Institute, who will speak on\n\u201cThe Way Out of Our Business De\npression.\u201d He will not confine himself\nto the building and loan business.\n\u201cWhither Home Ownership\u201d is the\nterse title listed for Leonard P. Resume,\npresident of the National Association of\nReal Estate Boards, who is expected to\nface the issue of apartment life en\ncroachment on the home idea.\nHome ownership will also be the\ntheme of ex-Gov. Chase Osborne of\nMichigan, who will address the general\nsessions on Thursday.\nOUTING TO BE HELD\nSfoster Plumbers\u2019 Program to Be\nObserved on July 30.\nFive hundred or more members and\nguest* of the Washington Master\nPlumber*\u2019 Association will Journey to\nChapel Point, Md\u201e July 30, for the 1930\nBummer outing of the organization.\nThe party will assemble at 8:30 at\nPeace Monument and leave there at 9\na.m. for the resort.\nAn old-fashioned shore dinner will\nbe served at noon. During the day\nthere will be swimming, fishing, quoits,\nhorseshoe pitching, races, dancing and\nhusband-calling contests. Many prizes\nWill be given to winners.\nThe program is being arranged by a\ncommittee consisting of Harry A. Scrog\ngins, chairman, and Thomas E. Clark,\nvice chairman. Frank A. Kerr, presi\ndent of the association, is supervising\nplans.\nFRIENDS FREE PRISONERS\nFARMINGTON, Utah, July 26 </P).\nThree men who came to the Davis\nCounty jail Thursday in an automobile\ncut a hole in the wall and released Roy\nThomas, 18. charged with beating and\nfobbing, and Elwood Adams, charged\nwith automobile theft. Two other pris\noners refused to escape and a third ran\nto notify officers.\n1 WOODRIDGE, D. C.\nISnni'Drlachd Brick\n1427 Kearney St. N.E.\nPrice, $6,500\nSSOO Canh \u2014$50 Monthly\nFive rooms, bath, sleeping, breakfast and front porches, hot-\nwater heat, hardwood floors throughout, fully screened by Woodward\nP Si Lothrop, large lot, nicely landscaped, large closets. 2 blocks from y\nft bus and stores, 3 blocks from Rhode Island Ave. street cars.\nHew te reach property\u2014Take bus marked Woodrtdse. eat oft 14th and Monroe. j|\nsouth to Reamer\u2014or anr Rhode Island Ave. cars to 14tn and Rhode Istand Avs., fi\nOpen for Ingpection Saturday Afternoon\nand All Day Sunday 1\nPhone Cleveland 7330\nM. and R. B. WARREN\nWASHINGTON, H. C. t\ns\nBOOKLET TO GIVE\nj POINTERS ON HOME\ni\nr j\nWood Utilization Committee\nr Group to Compile Work\nfor Buying Public.\ni Various points which should be con\nsidered in the purchase of a home will\nbe described in a booklet by a special\ncommittee of the National Committee\non Wood Utilization, it was announced\nthis week by Secretary of Commerce\nLamont. A number of Washington\nmen are members of the group ap\npointed for this work, which Is headed\nby N. Max Dunning of Chicago.\n\u201cA better understanding on the part\nof the home-buying- public in regard to\nthe principal structural and architec\ntural features of a house would give a\ndecided impetus to home ownership,\u201d\nsaid Mr. Dunning, in commenting on\nthe project. \u201cThe purchase of a home\nis the most important investment the\naverage person undertakes.\n\u201cAn understanding of materials and\nworkmanship and of what constitutes\ngood architecture, therefore, is of vital\nimportance to him in safeguarding his\ninvestment. These factors and many\nothers are to be studied in detail by the\nsubcommittee, and the results of their\nfindings incorporated in a bulletin\nunder the title \u2018How to Judge a House.\u2019\nThe National Committee on Wood\nUtilization, which was organized by\nHerbert Hoover as Secretary of Com\nmerce, has for its object the furthering\nof efficient wood-using practices. The\nnew bulletin will discuss the planning,\ndesigning and construction of houses\ncosting less than $15,000 in connection\nwith which wood Is used as an im\nportant structural or finishing material.\nBesides Mr. Dunning, the subcom\nmittee sponsoring this project and the\norganizations they represent, are as fol\nlows; Maj. W. D. Brookings, Chamber\nor Commerce of the United States,\nWashington; William F. Chew, National\nAssociation of Builders\u2019 Exchanges,\nBaltimore, Md.; Dr. John M. Cries,\nchief of division of public construc\ntion. Department of Commerce; Irving\nB. Hiett, National Association of Real\nEstate Boards. Toledo, Ohio; Le\u00dfoy E.\nKern, American Institute of Architects,\nWashington; William H. Miller, As\nsociated General Contractors of Ameri\nca, Cincinnati, Ohio; William S.\nQuinter, United States League of\nBuilding and Loan Associations, Wash\nington; L. J. Taber, National Orange,\nColumbus, Ohio; M. S. Winder, Ameri\ncan Farm Bureau Federation, Chicago,\nill., and James S. Taylor, chief. Divi\nsion of Building and Jfpu**Dg, Depart\nment of Commerce.\n144 HOMES TO RISE\nON BROOKLAND TRACT\nWork Started on Five-Year Pro\ngram of Detached Dwellings at\nTotal Cost of Million.\nA five-year program, calling for the\nconstruction of 144 detached dwellings\nof the colonial type, has been started\nby Sullivan Bros, on a 23-acre track\nof unimproved land In Brookland, east j\nof Catholic University and overlooking j\nMichigan Park.\nThe total estimated cost of con\nstructing the entire sections of houses\nas now planned is in excess of sl,-\n000.000.\nThe houses are being erected in the\nsection bounded by Eighteenth and\nTwenty-first streets. Michigan avenue\nand Varnum street, northeast. The\narea consists of the old Klein estate.\nUnder the plan adopted, develop\nment of the section is to be spread\nover a five or six year period, only a\nsmall number of houses being erected\nat one time.\nThe development Is the project of\nthe La Salle Park Corporation, with\nSullivan Bros., local realtors, as' the\nbuilding firm. The section is to be\ncalled La Salle Park. The houses all\nwill be of detached colonial type, of\nthree bed rooms and bath or four bed\nrooms and two-bath types. The\nbuilders now are engaged in opening\nand paving streets in the area pro\nvided for in the District highway plan.\n1 mm&L MBUA. 1\nGeorgian Type Home Has Attractive Features\nr\nLocated in Hewlett Bay\nPark, It Overlooks\nWillow Pond.\nPLANTING HELPS\nITS APPEARANCE\nProperty Was Practically De\nvoid of Trees When Work\nStarted in 1925.\nr 1\u2014\nThe house illustrated here 1s probably\ntypical of many medium-priced houses\nerected In recent years on the South\nShore of Long Island. The property is\nsituated in the Hewlett Bay Park, over\nlooking Willow Pond, with a view south\ntoward the Macy Channel.\nThe house is chaste in design and the\nproportions are carefully studied. The\ncontrast between the brick walls and\nthe white trim is charming.\nThe entrance is almost austere in its\nconception and symbolizes the best of\nour Colonial work. Another attractive\nfeature is the solid window heads on\nthe ground floor. The planting around\nthe house is well placed and enhances\nthe setting of the building. Restraint in\ncountrv house work is pleasing to see\nand gives a subtle dignity to the whole\ncomposition.\nAs is the case with so many places\non the South Shore, the property was\npractically devoid of trees except for a\nfew fairly good sized ones on the shore\nof the pond. The house was built in\n1925. The photographs of the place\nshow what has been and can be accom\nplished in five years toward a general\nplanting development.\nDesigns Vary Widely.\nThe house is in the Georgian style\nand of frame construction, veneered\nwith brick. The roof is of slate. The\nexterior trim is of white pine and the\narches and panels of the first floor are\nof white stucco. The loggia has a\nheather brown tile floor with rough\ncast plaster walls and ceilings. Owing\nto the low elevation of the property\nabove the pond, the cellar had to be\nwaterproofed.\nThe American house is of many and\nveried designs. Probably nowhere in\nthe world is an architect called upon\nto design residences in ao many differ\nent styles of architecture as in America.\nIn this country every known foreign\nstyle is used. Generally speaking, Amer\nican owners have more or less fixed in\ntheir minds the type of house they wish\nto have, and almost invariably their\nproperty is selected without consulting\nan architect. The architect must then\nget to work and with the property plan\ndetermine and try to solve the problem\nIn the style desired by the owners, plus\nthe usual stipulations as to special ar\nrangements of rooms, porches and last\nbut not least, the question of cost.\nCompromise Required.\nConstruction materials must be se\nlected to come within the amount to\nbe spent, allowance must be set aside\nfor grading, roads, gardens and general\nplanting. Rarely will an owner give in\nto reducing the size of a house in order\nto reduce the cost. This is one of the\nmost difficult problems confronting the\narchitect. The medium-priced bouse is\nthe most difficult problem for the archi\ntect to work out, but we find that all\nproblems can be solved in a satisfactory\nmanner with a frank, thorough and\nhonest understanding with the owner.\nToo much emphasis cannot be laid\non the preliminary work with a client.\nIn the majority of cases everything can\nbe decided and cleared up with prelimi\nnary sketches, studies and estimates.\nThere must also be a compromise be\ntween owner and architect.\nSHOP LEASES BUSINESS\nPROPERTY AT 1227 G\nRental for Nearly Four Tears Re\nported as s3o,ooo\u2014Furriers Take\nSpace on Eleventh Street.\nBusiness property at 1327 G street\nhas been leased by the Ming Toy Dress\nand Hat Shop for nearly four years, it\nwas announced today by Carl G. Rosin\nski. The total rental consideration was\nreported to be approximately $30,000.\nEanet St Bacher, furriers, have leased\nbusiness property at 717 Eleventh street\nfor a term of three years for a rental\nconsideration totaling approximately\n$7,500, it is reported also by the Rosin\nski office.\n2 Charming Individual Homes Complete!!\nr TX) the smallest detail in construction and of the best modern\nequipment, in the fastest growing home development of the\nbetter type in this section.\nIn Beautiful La Salle Park\n7 and 8 Rooms and 2 Baths\u2014Garage\nNos. i -m; i\u2014 si. n.E.\nPriced from *12,950 to *13,500\nOpen for Inspecton Daily\u2014Sunday Until 9 PM.\nSULLIVAN BROS.\n819 15th St. N.W.\nPhone Metro. 4323 s! NM. j\nW)t %umm Jlkf.\nV. wrm wtwmt woumra wamm\njP' Ilf Kki WKKsStij? I\nfVlgrifmf'i\nXl* 'J&jj&m\nwL H| \\ZJUSBmmt\n\u25a0UgM\nSi fc\n''HkhL jL\nV V /\"Wl\n-sJ( rtj 4 tbL\n1 HOME DECISION HAILED\nThe recent decision by the Court of\nAppeals sustaining the constitutional\nity of section 300 of the multiple\ndwelling law definitely establishes the\n\u201cprofessional status and responsibility\nof registered architects in the State of\nNew York.\u201d says an editorial in the\nArchitectural Forum.\n\"The essential character of the vari\nous phases of engineering germane to\nbuilding construction is recognized,\u201d\nthe editorial says. \"The architect is,\nhowever, justified in demanding that\nengineers be so registered as to iden\ntify their special training, knowledge\nand competency, which will automati\ncally place all of the building Industry\nprofessionals on a higher professional\nplane comparable to that set up by the\narchitects\u2019 registration law.\u201d\n$700,000 APARTMENT\nIS PLANNED BY STERN\nSite at Connecticut and Brandy\nwine, With Frontage of 107\nFeet, Is to Be Used.\nPlans for the construction of an\neight-story apartment house, having a\ncost estimated at $700,000, on a site\nat the southwest corner of Connecti\ncut avenue and Brandywine street,\nhave been filed with the District build\ning Inspector by David L. Stem, local\narchitect and builder.\nThe proposed structure would be of\nbrick and stone construction and have\na frontage of 107 feet on the avenue,\na depth of approximately 145 feet and\na height of 90 feet.\nSATTRDAY, JULY 26. 1930.\nSeveral Points Are to Be\nBorne in Mind When\nPlanning Garden.\nITS RELATION TO\nHOUSE ESSENTIAL\nHidden Nooks and Surprises\nAdd Greater Charm\nand Interest.\nBY JEANNE M. BROOKS.\nEach year brings us greater tempta\ntions and better facilities for creating\na garden. Whether it be large or small,\nin the country, in a back yard or\\ even\non a roof, the opportunities are un\nlimited.\nTo some gardening is an art, to others\na sport, and to a few a dissipation. It\ntakes firm self-denial on the part of a\ntrue garden lover to abandon a day\u2019s\npottering among his plants to attend the\nuninteresting chores of housekeeping.\nPerhaps, too, it might be whispered that\ngardening is a great compensation for\nmiddle age.\nGardens of Many Types Possible.\nThe types of gardens are many and\nthe pleasures of all are limitless. The\nsimple hardy border of perennials gives\nan array of color and beauty from early\nSpring through the Autumn. The sunk\nen garden is more secluded; in fact, it\nis almost an outdoor room; while a rock\ngarden is a veritable treasure chest of\ntiny plants.\nWhen planning the garden several\nessential points should be considered,\none of the most important being its\nrelation to the house, both in type and\nsituation. What could be more incon\ngruous than an elaborate formal garden\nadjoining a simple cottage?\nSurprises Enhance Garden.\nIf the boundaries of a small estate\nare cleverly concealed by planting, the\nbeauty of the property will be greatly\nenhanced and the plot will appear\nlarger. When possible, avoid having all\nof the garden in view at the same time.\nLittle hidden nooks and surprises add\ngreater charm and interest to both large i\nand small gardens.\nMake your vistas as long as possible\nand keep large open spaces of lawn.\nBird baths and feeding shelters will\nquickly attract the birds If kept replen\nished. A limited amount of suitable\ngarden furniture placed in sheltered po- i\nsitions affords a restful spot to view this 1\nyear's accomplishments and dream of 1\nnext year\u2019s improvements.\nHOSIERY FIRM LEASES\nQUARTERS AT 1205 F ST. j\nProperty on Connecticut Avenue\nand Eighteenth Street Taken\nby Other Concerns.\nBusiness quarters at ISOS P street\nhave been leased by the Golden Dawn\nHosiery Co. for a term of 15 years\nfor an undisclosed rental consideration,\nit was announced today by Shannon\nSt Luchs, Inc., which handled the\ntransaction. After alterations, the\nconcern will open there the twenty\nfirst chain unit of the hosiery com\npany, which has headquarters in\nPhiladelphia.\nLee D. Butler, Inc., has leased the\nautomobile show room quarters at 1132\nConnecticut avenue and business prop\nerty at 2447 Eighteenth street has been\nleased to the Atlantic St Pacific Tea\nCo. for a possible term of seven years\nat a rental approximating SI,BOO a\nyear. Shannon St Luchs also report.\nThe latter property is owned by W.\nGwynn Gardner, formerly a member of\nthe board of District commissioners.\nShuman St Co., shoe dealers, have\nleased business quarters at 704 Seventh\nstreet, for a term of more than four\nyears, for a rental of approximately $3,-\n600 per year, it is announced.\nH 7100 MEADOW LANE, CHEVY CHASE 2\nr _ T /A\nj I HE third house to be ready in (the first two\nJl were sold on completion) is the charming New England\nJl Colonial shown above, occupying a most desirable corner lot, com-\nH pletely sodded and attractively landscaped, with a delightful small A\nformal garden and a handsome willow tree on the side lawn. A\nBuilt of stone and white weatherboard, with a center hall, J\nit contains six spacious rooms, two baths, floored attic, built-in X\nj 2-car garage and wide covered side porch. There are Celotex\nJl insulated walls. General Electric Refrigerator,' built-in kitchen\nJl cabinets, Sanitas (washable) walls, and other features.\n/I Inspect this home at your earliest convenience. Drive out JR\nJl Connecticut Avenue to Columbia Country Club, turn west (left), A\nen Betheeda~Silver Spring Highway, one black to f\nIt f rdowbrook J|\nA WARREN DEVELOPMENT <TW.\nIEXm ,N CHEVY cmase\nPRIVATE BUILDING HERE\nHITS $320,300 FOR WEEK\ni-\nNew List of Projects Given Approval Include\n$150,000 Home for Col. D. B. DeVore.\n$1,000,000 Apartment Permit Asked.\nPRIVATE building operations in the District for which plans\nwere approved during the past week by the building inspector.\nCol. John W. Oehmann, have a total cost estimated at $320,300.\nIncluded in the new list of work were plans for a home for\nCol. D. B. DeVore at 2000 Twenty-fourth street, having a cost esti\nmated at $150,000. Charles D. Sager obtained permits for construc\ntion of 10 twoi-story brick dwellings in theh 500 block of Twenty\nthird street northeast, having a total cost of $50,000.\nForecasting a projected future development of large size, the\nWestchester Development Corporation this week applied to the\nbuilding Inspector for a permit for the construction of an eight\nstory apartment building at 3900 Cathedral avenue, the cost of\nwhich is estimated at $1,000,000.\nThis building would be the third\nstructure of the huge apartment de\nvelopment started on the 28-acre tract\nlying along Cathedral avenue between\nThirty-ninth street and the Glover\nparkway. The first two buildings now\nare nearing completion.\nThe proposed third Unit would con\ntain 91 apartment suites. It would\nhave a frontage of 127 feet and a depth\nof 203 feet. Harvey Warwick is the\narchitect.\nCol. DeVore Will Build.\nProjects for which permits were is\nsued during the past week include the\nfollowing:\nCol. D. B. DeVore, owner: Bottomly.\nWagner White, New' York City, de\nsigners; R. W. Bolling, builder; to erect\none 2-story brick and limestone dwell\ning, 2000 Twenty-fourth street (lot 13,\nsquare 2503), to cost $150,000.\nCharles D. Sager, owner and builder;\nGeorge T. Santmyers, architect; to erect\nten 2-story brick dwellings, 518 to 536\nTwenty-third street northeast (lots 101\nto 110, square 4516), to cost $50,000.\nW. W. Vaughn, owner, designer and\nbuilder; to erect two 2-story brick and\ncinder block dwellings, 1025 Varnum\nstreet and 4316 Twelfth street north\neast (lots 137 and 138, square 3891); to\ncost $14,200.\nFrank L. Fanning, owner and build\ner; L. W. Giles, architect; to erect one\n2-story brick and frame dwelling. 7545\nAlaska avenue (lot 59, square 2955), to\ncost $14,000.\nW. C. N. A. Miller, owners\nand builders; Gordon E. Mac Neil. arch\nitect; to erect one 2 4 -story brick and\nframe dwelling, 4434 Garfield street\n(part lots 17 to 21, square 1615), to\ncost $13,400.\nHome Will Cost $12,500.\nW. C. N. A. Miller, owners\nand builders; Gordon E. Mac Neil, arch\nitect; to erect one 2'/ 2 -story stone and\nframe dwelling, 4341 Forest lane (lot\n75. square 1619), to cost $12,500.\nW. C. N. A. Miller, owners\nand builders; Gordon E. Mac Neil, arch\nitect; to erect one 2*/2-story stucco,\nbrick and frame dwelling. 4331 Forest\nlane (lot 74, square 1619), to cost\n$lO,BOO.\nLeo J. Mansuy, owner; G. M. Ram-\nB Chevy\n4508 Ridge St.\nJust Norths of Chevy Chase Country CJub\nTo intvect\u2014Drive out Connecticut Avenue to Bradley Lane, turn west on Bradley\nLane three squares to Bast Ave., then north on East Ave. one block to Ridge St.\nCome Out Sunday\u2014Often Daily Until 9 P.M.\nM. R. B. WARREN\nOperator^\nReliable and Dependable Tel. Wisconsin 2873\nBUILDING NEWS\nI say, designer; to erect one 2-story brick\nand stone gasoline service station. 4401\nConnecticut avenue (part of parcel\ni 57/73, square 2046), to cost $11,500.\nL. E. Breunlnger Sons, owners and\nbuilders; H. L. Breunlnger. architect: to\nerect one 2* 2 -story brick and stucco\ndwelling. 1354 Juniper street (lot 12,\nl square W-2774), to cost $9,000.\n1 Phlllipo Dellacassa. owner; N. F.\ni Baessell, builder; to erect one 2-story\nbrick and stucco dwelling. 3361 Military\nroad (lot 15, square 1992), to cost\n$8,500.\n.1 6119 WESTERN\nAVENUE I\n1 Chevy Chase, D. C.\ni y 1\nI *17,950\n11\nFIRST SHOWING jj\n\u2014of new brick and tile\ny home with 2-car garage, n\nEquipped with copper gut- i;\nters and downspouts, cop- U\ny per screens, metal weather- I\nm strips and Kelvinator.\nThree Blocks East of\ny Chevy Chase Circle\nOpen Sunday\n11 AM to 9 PM. I\n1 iienry J. Connor\n3221 Co\u00a3n. Ave.\nI Clev. 4859\nB-1","height":"25371","width":"19785"}}
